  <title>Examples A</title>
  
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Mag. Flux</title>
    

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A small particle of mass 2 g and charge <m>10 \,\mu C</m> is emitted at <m>t = 0</m> 
      from the origin with the velocity <m>\vec{v} = 3 \,(m/s) \hat{i}+ 4 \,(m/s) \hat{k}</m> 
      in a uniform magnetic field of strength <m>100 \,T </m>in the z-direction. If there 
      is no electrical field and no gravity, 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          what is the force on the particle at t = 0? 
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the magnitude and direction of the acceleration of the particle at t = 0? 
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the radius of the helix about which the particle moves?
        </li>
        <li>
          How long does it take the particle to complete one revolution of its motion?
        </li>
        <li>
          How far along the z-direction has the particle moved during this revolution?
        </li>
      </ol>
       </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Given: 
     <m>m = 2.0\times10^{-3}\,kg;</m> 
     <m>q = 1.0\times10^{-5}\,C;</m> 
     <m> \vec{v} = 3 \,(m/s) \hat{i}+ 4 \,(m/s) \hat{k};</m>
     <m>\vec{B}= 100 \,T \hat{k}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Equations:  
      <me>
        vec{F}  = q(\vec{E} + \vec{v} \times \vec{B});
      </me>
      <me>
        \vec{F}  = m\vec{a};
      </me>
      <me>
        v_{\perp} = v_{x} = \vec{v}\cdot\hat{i};
      </me>
      <me>
        a=\frac{v^{2}_{\perp}}{r};
      </me>
      <me>
        z = v_{z}t
      </me>
         </p>
         <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <m>\vec{F}= -3.0\times10^{-3}N\hat{j}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
             <m>a = 1.5\,(m/s^{2});  </m>
             <m>\quad \hat{a}=-\hat{j};</m>
             <m>\quad v_{\perp}= 3\,(m/s)</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>r = 6 \,m</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t - 12.6 \,s</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m> z= 50.2\, m </m>
            </li>
          </ol>
         </p>
       </solution>
</example>


<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If a proton <m>(m_{p} = 1.673 \times 10^{-27} \,kg,</m> <m>q_{p} = e = 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \,C)</m> 
      is accelerated through a potential difference of 100 V, 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          what is its velocity?
        </li>
        <li>
          If it passes through a velocity selector and then into a region of space containing 
          only a uniform magnetic field perpendicular to the velocity, what is the strength of 
          that field if the diameter of the proton's orbit is 50 cm?
        </li>
        <li>
          If the magnetic field in the velocity selector is the same as that in part b, 
          what is the strength of the electric field in the velocity selector?
        </li>
        <li>
          If a deuteron <m>(m_{d} = 2 m_{p},\quad q_{d} = q_{p})</m> is to pass through the same velocity selector, 
          through what potential difference must it be accelerated?
        </li>
        <li>
          What then is the diameter of its orbit in the uniform magnetic field region?
        </li>
      </ol>
        </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Given: <m>m_{p} = 1.673\times10^{-27}\,kg;\quad q_{p} = 1.602\times10^{-19}\,C;</m>
      <m>V_{p}=100 \,V;\quad  r_{p}=0.25 \,m;\quad  m_{d}=2m_{p};\quad q_{d} =q_{p}</m> 
    </p>
    <p>
      Equations: 
         <me>
        \frac{1}{2}m_{p}v^{2} = q_{p}V_{p};
      </me>
      <me>
        F = q_{p}v B = \frac{m_{p}v^{2}}{r_{p}};
      </me>
      <me>
        \vec{F}=q(\vec{E}+\vec{v}\times\vec{B})=0 
      </me>
      <me>
        E = v_{p}B;
      </me>
      <me>
        \frac{1}{2}m_{d}v^{2} = q_{d}V_{d};
      </me>
      <me>
        F = q_{d}v B = \frac{m_{d}v^{2}}{r_{d}};
      </me>
      <me>
        D_{d} = 2r_{d}
      </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
           <me>
            v = 1.38\times10^{5} \,m/s
           </me>
           
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              B =  5.78 \times10^{-3} \,T
            </me>
            
          </li>
          <li>
           <me>
            E = 800 \,V/m
           </me>
           
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              V_{d}= 200 \,V; \quad r_{d}= 0.5 \,m
            </me>
            
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              D_{d}= 1.0 \,m 
            </me>
            
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The plane of a circle of radius 10 cm makes an angle of <m>30^{o}</m> with a uniform magnetic field. 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          If the magnetic flux through this circle is <m>50 W_{b},</m> what is the strength of the magnetic field? 
        </li>
        <li>
          If a magnetic field is given in MKS units by <m>B = 2y + yz,</m> 
          what is the magnetic flux through a square whose corners are at (0,0,0), (0,1m,0), (0,1m,1m), and (0,0,1m)?
        </li>
      </ol>
         </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Given: <m>r = 0.1 \,m; \quad \theta = 30^{o}; \quad  \Phi_{B}=50 W_{b};</m> <m> \quad \vec{B}= 2y\hat{i}+yz\hat{k}</m>
         </p>
         <p>
          Equations:
          <me>
            \Phi_{B} = \int\vec{B}\cdot\vec{\,dA} = \vec{B}\cdot\vec{A} = BA\cos\theta = BA; 
          </me>
          <me>
            A = \pi r^{2}
          </me>
         <me>
          \vec{dA} = \,dy\,dz \hat{i};
         </me>
         <me>
          \Phi_{B} = \int\vec{B}\cdot\vec{\,dA} = \iint2y\,dy\,dz = \int\limits_{0}^{1}2y\,dy  \int\limits_{0}^{1}\,dz 
         </me>
         <me>
          = \left.y^{2}\right]_{0}^{1} \left.z\right|_{0}^{1} = 1
         </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
               <me>
                A = 0.0314 \,m^{2};
               </me>
               <me>
                B = 3.18\times10^{3}\, T
               </me>
               
              </li>
              <li>
              <me>
                \Phi_{B}= 1.0 \,W_{b}
              </me>
              
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
</example>

</paragraphs>


<paragraphs>
  <title>Mag. Force</title>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The cube shown at below is 0.5 m on a side. The wire bent as shown carries a current of 0.2 A 
        and the uniform magnetic field in the +x direction is 10 T. Find the magnitude and direction 
        of the magnetic force on each segment of the wire.
      </p>
      <image source="fig46.png" width="35%"> </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given:	<m>a = 0.5 \,m; \quad I = 0.2 \,A; \quad \vec{B}  = 10 \,T \hat{i} </m> 
        <me>
          \vec{F}=I\vec{l}\times\vec{B}
        </me>
         <me>
          (ab) \quad \vec{l}=a\hat{k};
         </me>
           <me>
            (bc) \quad \vec{l}=a\hat{i}-a\hat{k};
           </me>
           <me>
            (cd) \quad \vec{l}=-a\hat{j};
           </me>
         <me>
          (de) \quad \vec{l}=a\hat{j}+a\hat{k};
         </me>
         <me>
          (ef) \quad \vec{l}=-a\hat{i}-a\hat{j}- a\hat{k}
         </me>
        </p> 
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <me>
                \text{Along (ab)} \quad \vec{F} = 1.00\,N \hat{j}; 
               </me>
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \text{Along (bc)}  \quad \vec{F} = 1.00\,N [-\hat{j}]
               </me>
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \text{Along (cd)}  \quad  \vec{F} = 1.00\,N \hat{k};
              </me>
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \text{Along (de)} \quad  \vec{F} = 1.41 \,N \left[\frac{\hat{j}-\hat{k}}{\sqrt{2}}\right]
              </me>
            </li>
            <li>
              <me>
                \text{Along (ef)}\quad \vec{F} = 1.41 \,N \left[\frac{-\hat{j}+\hat{k}}{\sqrt{2}}\right] 
              </me>
            </li>
          </ol>
         </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A circular coil of wire 20 cm in diameter with 100 turns of wire is centered at 
        the origin in the x/z plane as shown in the figure below. The coil contains a 
        current of 100 mA in the direction shown and is located in a uniform magnetic 
        field of magnitude 10 T pointing in the direction of <m>30^{o}</m> above the x-axis. 
        <image source="fig47.png" width="35%"> </image>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            What is the magnetic flux through the coil? 
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the magnetic moment of the coil?
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the magnetic torque on the coil? 
          </li>
          <li>
            About what axis would the coil rotate if it were allowed to rotate freely?
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the magnetic potential energy of the coil? 
          </li>
        </ol>
         </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given: <m>r=0.1\,m;\quad N= 100; \quad I = 0.1\,A; \quad B=10\,T; \quad \theta=30^{o}</m>
          <me>
            \vec{B}=B\cos\theta\hat{i}+B\sin\theta\hat{j};
          </me>
          <me>
            \vec{A}=\pi r^{2}\hat{j}
          </me>
          <me>
            \Phi_{B}=\int \vec{B}\cdot\vec{dA}=\vec{B}\cdot\vec{A};
          </me>
          <me>
            \vec{\mu}=NI\vec{A};
          </me>
          <me>
            \vec{\tau}=\vec{\mu}\times\vec{B};
          </me>
          <me>
            U = -\vec{\mu}\cdot\vec{B}
          </me>
           </p>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
           <me>
            \Phi_{B}=\pi r^{2}B\sin\theta = 0.157 W_{b}
           </me>
           
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \vec{\mu}=0.314 Am^{2}\hat{j} 
            </me>
            
          </li>
          <li>
           <me>
            \vec{\tau}= -2.72 Nm\hat{k} 
           </me>
           
          </li>
          <li>
            z-axis 
          </li>
          <li>
            U = -1.57 Joule.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>
